<p><strong>The Oaks and Mountain View Estates.</strong> Premium gated communities above Las Virgenes Road. Homes run 4,000 to 7,000 square feet with dedicated laundry rooms and proper vent installations. The LG machines we service here tend to be top-of-line: LG Signature series, DLGX6501, DLEX9500 steam models. These are absolutely worth repairing — a heating element replacement ($300–380) or drum bearing ($320–400) on a machine that cost $1,500+ new is straightforward math. The calls we get from The Oaks are usually mechanical wear on machines 8–12 years old. Last fall we had a call from a home on Park Mirador — LG Signature DLEX9500, about 9 years old, starting to make a low rhythmic thump every cycle. Drum rollers. We replaced all four plus the idler pulley while the drum was out — $280–350 total, done in 90 minutes. The homeowner had assumed the machine was at end of life. It wasn't close. Mountain dust conditions in this part of Calabasas accelerate wear on moving parts — we see roller wear on machines in these communities at 7–8 years that we'd expect at 10–12 years in a flat urban setting. When we get a no-heat call and find error code PS alongside d80 or d90, we check the full vent path — PS indicates the dryer has detected a pressure sensor issue from restricted airflow.</p>

